<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>What are general education courses?</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>General education courses are generalized classes that colleges often require students to take in addition to their degree-related classes. They may not directly relate to a student's degree but are a requirement of graduation. These general education classes often educate students in a variety of foundational subjects and soft skills, which are personal habits or traits that influence one's work.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>General education classes expand on secondary level knowledge, providing an advanced undergraduate understanding of interdisciplinary studies, such as English, mathematics, science and history. Post-secondary students are often allowed choice in the variety of classes that meet a requirement and can customize requirements to their interests. For example, they may be able to choose biology, chemistry, ecology or astronomy to meet a science requirement.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Related:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/resumes-cover-letters/hard-skills-vs-soft-skills" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><strong>Hard Skills vs. Soft Skills</strong></a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>What are the benefits of classes that teach general education skills?</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There are many benefits of taking general education skills classes. General education classes give you the opportunity to:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Build and practice soft skills:</strong>&nbsp;General education classes allow you to build and practice soft skills, such as communication and leadership. These skills are often requested by many employers and can make you a more competitive candidate when applying for positions.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Improve skills that assist with education:</strong>&nbsp;The general knowledge and soft skills that you learn in general education classes not only applies to the workforce but also to academic settings. For example, an excellent foundation in writing, environmental science and teamwork skills can enable innovation and greater success in a group civil engineering project.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Create a resume with desirable skills:</strong>&nbsp;If you're newly graduated or still an entry-level employee, general education skills from your general education classes can provide content for your resume. You can build an immediate functional resume that focuses on these skills instead of limited experience.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Identify skills you can use when interviewing:</strong>&nbsp;The same skills that you develop in your general education classes can help you form and practice interview answers. This is especially beneficial when answering behavioral interview questions that are common in interviews.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Learn lifelong learning skills:</strong>&nbsp;General classes can also help you develop a new perspective on learning. They provide a general foundation of inquiry that can encourage you to continue learning knowledge and skills long after graduation.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Develop a new perspective on diversity and the world:</strong>&nbsp;Taking general classes can challenge students to consider cultures and perspectives different from their own. This helps to prepare you for a diverse workforce, regardless of the career or type of position that you choose.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
